WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.000
 (upbeat jazz music)

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:12.440
 Hello, and welcome to Django for Everybody.

00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:14.800
 Today we're gonna talk about using the shell.

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:16.680
 It's one of the early assignments in the class,

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:19.600
 and I just kinda wanna walk you through things.

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:20.640
 Now you might ask yourself,

00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:23.880
 why are we using this old-fashioned command line interface?

00:00:23.880 --> 00:00:26.160
 Everything that I do is pointing quick, clicky,

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:28.280
 or I just move my finger and things work.

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:30.600
 And the answer is yes, for end users,

00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:32.560
 we try to make things as easy as possible,

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:36.720
 but there's always a server behind that kind of cool stuff

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:37.840
 that you're building.

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:40.760
 And that server, 99% of the time,

00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:43.160
 doesn't have a clicky graphical user interface,

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:46.320
 it has a command line interface, a textual interface,

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:47.160
 where it gives you a prompt,

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:48.360
 you type some stuff and you hit enter,

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:50.440
 you type some more stuff and you hit enter.

00:00:50.440 --> 00:00:55.440
 And Linux is by far the most popular server system

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:56.560
 on the planet.

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:00.040
 And so if you're anywhere near the server,

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:02.920
 it doesn't hurt to understand a little bit how this works.

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:04.520
 You don't have to be a wizard,

00:01:04.520 --> 00:01:06.280
 but the whole idea of this assignment

00:01:06.280 --> 00:01:09.360
 is to give you some sense of what you're dealing with

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:12.800
 and weird things that might happen

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:14.840
 while you're using this command line.

00:01:14.840 --> 00:01:17.440
 So we're gonna use Python Anywhere as we do in the class,

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:21.280
 but the concept of the shell and the Linux user interface,

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:23.640
 that's universal across servers.

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:25.440
 Python Anywhere just gives you a free one.

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:28.080
 Otherwise, you'd get one from Amazon or Google

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:30.000
 or Windows Azure.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.280
 So here you are, you're logged into Python Anywhere.

00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:35.320
 You go into the consoles tab and you can start a new console.

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:38.280
 And the console, you can just run Python interactively

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:39.240
 if you want.

00:01:39.240 --> 00:01:41.200
 You can run a MySQL shell that connects

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:43.720
 to your MySQL database, which we'll have later.

00:01:43.720 --> 00:01:46.720
 I prefer to not use any of these things

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:49.040
 except the bash shell.

00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:52.680
 The bash is just, there's variations

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:54.520
 in the Linux user interface.

00:01:54.520 --> 00:01:56.320
 And bash is just one of them.

00:01:56.320 --> 00:01:57.920
 And so you may not use bash.

00:01:57.920 --> 00:02:01.400
 You may use the SH or something else,

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:04.240
 but they all kind of have common things

00:02:04.240 --> 00:02:06.320
 with little tiny subtle differences.

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:08.000
 So I'm gonna start a bash shell.

