 in an error message.

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:33.400
 So that's the shell interface, and again,

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:36.080
 part of what I wanna show you is for you to know

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:37.520
 when you're talking to the shell,

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:39.280
 'cause you're not always talking to the shell.

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:40.840
 If it ends in a dollar sign prompt,

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:42.320
 usually you're talking to the shell.

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:44.160
 So let's take a look at what it might look like

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:46.440
 in different situations.

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:49.280
 So sometimes you just run Python interactively,

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:50.640
 and if you've taken a Python course,

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:54.760
 this is the REPL, the read, evaluate, something loop.

00:09:54.760 --> 00:09:57.760
 So you just type Python,

00:09:57.760 --> 00:09:59.360
 and it's running Python interactively.

00:09:59.360 --> 00:10:02.240
 Now you're still sitting in a prompt, okay?

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:05.540
 And so now that's not the same thing.

00:10:05.540 --> 00:10:07.000
 That's not Linux talking to you,

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:08.400
 that's Python talking to you.

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:10.440
 You're running the command Python on Linux,

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:12.920
 and that Python command is asking for input.

00:10:12.920 --> 00:10:15.120
 So it expects you to type Python.

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:18.760
 Hello world, of course we're gonna type hello world.

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:23.060
 And that reads the Python, parses it, and then executes it.

00:10:23.060 --> 00:10:25.360
 Now if you're in this and you type ls,

00:10:25.360 --> 00:10:26.680
 it's like I don't know what to do.

00:10:26.680 --> 00:10:30.040
 I have no idea, pwd, I have no idea what you're doing,

00:10:30.040 --> 00:10:31.640
 'cause you're not in the shell.

00:10:31.640 --> 00:10:33.240
 So students come to me and go like,

00:10:33.240 --> 00:10:36.280
 I keep typing pwd and it's giving me name errors.

00:10:36.280 --> 00:10:39.260
 Like, well, that's 'cause you're in Python, not in the shell.

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:41.640
 So you have to know how to exit.

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:44.960
 And you do that with quit, open paren, close paren, enter.

00:10:44.960 --> 00:10:48.340
 And now you're back to the happy little dollar sign prompt.

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:51.160
 And now you can say pwd and it will work, right?

00:10:51.160 --> 00:10:55.160
 So part of it is recognizing what you're interacting with

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:57.680
 based on what the prompt looks like.

00:10:57.680 --> 00:11:00.000
 Okay, so that's the Python interface.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:05.000
 Now, if you end up with a more than one line Python statement,

00:11:05.920 --> 00:11:09.440
 that three chevrons prompts turns into a dot, dot, dot.

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:10.760
 Let me show you how that works.

00:11:10.760 --> 00:11:12.200
 So I'm gonna run Python again.

00:11:12.200 --> 00:11:14.920
 I'm just cursoring up Python.

00:11:14.920 --> 00:11:19.920
 And I can say for i in range five, colon.

00:11:19.920 --> 00:11:24.000
 Now you see that the prompt is turned into a dot, dot, dot.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:25.500
 And I have to do an indent, of course.

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:28.640
 One, two, three, four, five, print i.

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:32.480
 And it's still thinking that I'm in this for loop.

00:11:32.480 --> 00:11:34.280
 And so it's saying, are you still doing more stuff

00:11:34.280 --> 00:11:35.100
 in the for loop?

00:11:35.100 --> 00:11:36.440
 Let me put another line in this for loop.

00:11:36.440 --> 00:11:40.640
 I could say print second line.

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:44.680
 And then I can hit the enter and say,

00:11:44.680 --> 00:11:45.960
 I'm done with the for loop.

00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:48.280
 And then we'll actually read the for loop,

00:11:48.280 --> 00:11:50.480
 run the for loop, execute it five times

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:52.640
 with i being zero, one, two, three, four.

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:54.760
 But the body loop has two things.

00:11:54.760 --> 00:11:57.240
 And then when it's done with this sort of continuation,

00:11:57.240 --> 00:12:00.280
 dot, dot, dot is like, I need more, I'm not done yet.

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:02.600
 Whatever you typed, it's not finished.

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:05.160
 Now I'm back to the standard Chevron prompt,

00:12:05.160 --> 00:12:06.920
 at which case I would type quit.

00:12:06.920 --> 00:12:09.960
 And now I'm back to the shell prompt.

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:11.960
 See, the whole idea is to be able to record,

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:14.520
 it's like, don't get lost because it's asking,

00:12:14.520 --> 00:12:16.180
 you're talking to the wrong thing.

00:12:16.180 --> 00:12:19.560
 Okay, so that's one thing.

00:12:19.560 --> 00:12:23.760
 Now, later we'll have you talking to your database.

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:26.240
 And SQLite is one of the databases that we use.

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:30.780
 And so we can, I'm gonna go back into my home directory,

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:34.520
 cd pwd ls.

00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:37.200
 And so we see this file db.sqlite3,

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:39.840
 that is where SQLite stores its data.

